SUMMARY:  On January 18, 2019, Thomas Long, Legal Director, and Katy Morsony, Staff Attorney, with The Utility Reform Network (TURN) met with Sean Simon, advisor to Cmmr. Rechtschaffen. TURN representatives discussed the Commission’s review of the Wildfire Mitigation Plans due to be filed by California electric utilities on February 6, 2019. TURN stated its interest in a Wildfire Mitigation Plan proceeding that results in utility service that is safe, reliable and affordable. TURN stated that it is encouraged by Administrative Law Judge Thomas’s January 17 Ruling directing that the Wildfire Mitigation Plans include the TURN template segregating existing compliance requirements already reflected in Commission approved rates and new or discretionary proposals that have not yet been approved by the Commission. TURN representatives, however, stated that it is mindful that the plans that the Commission adopts will become compliance requirements, subject to penalty, against which utilities will be measured by an independent evaluator. TURN recommended that this proceeding also focus on nuts and bolts issues, like clarification of operational practices and procedures, inspection protocols, emergency preparedness and response, and performance metrics and monitoring. TURN noted that the abbreviated time schedule and compliance requirements, leave R.18-10-007 an insufficient forum for the review and approval of new major spending programs.

SUMMARY:  On December 5, 2018, counsel to East Bay Municipal Utility District (EBMUD) sent a cover email message and attached PDF document titled “East Bay Municipal Utility District Suggested Additions to Draft IOU Template for Wildfire Mitigation Plans” to a service list that included at least one decisionmaker (President Picker’s advisor David Peck). EBMUD submits this notice in an abundance of caution and to ensure compliance with the December 26, 2018 ruling. Written materials relevant to the communication are attached to the notice.

SUMMARY:  [Pursuant to the Ruling of December 26, 2018] On December 4 and 5, 2018, Rachael Koss on behalf of the Coalition of California Utility Employees (CUE) sent electronic mails to Tom Long of The Utility Reform Network. The e-mails concerned the template for the electric utilities’ wildfire mitigation plans. Ms. Koss’ email stated that CUE opposed TURN’s proposal to include costs in the template since SB 901 prohibits cost from being considered in a wildfire mitigation plan and instead requires cost to be considered in a general rate case. Copies of the correspondence are attached to the notice.
